OK, I played some more with this, and I am able to reproduce it on master, and it seems that it has to do with the height of the container you have around your text fields.  If I make it 34 pixels high or less (instead of the media query calculation you have), then I get the broken behavior, but if I make it 35 pixels high or more, everything works. Because you're using the media query calculation, making it fullscreen changes that size.

So, if I had to guess, this has something to do with the container constraints being smaller than the size that a text field or it's decoration wants to be. It's not overflowing the container because the text field can be small heights, but maybe something in the text field is calculating bounds that the traversal system doesn't like?

It's definitely a bug, since it shouldn't be rejecting the other fields, but it's probably not that common of an arrangement, which is why we haven't seen it until now.

Here's the app I used to test with. I changed some things from your example just to see if it had to do with the `Grid` widget, or other constraints. If you slide the slider to 34 or below, you'll see the broken behavior, and if you slide it to 35, it'll go away.

